			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3769">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p><em><strong>This is a portion of a letter to John Rosenthal about his essay, &ldquo;<a href="/article/2263">Insisting On Love</a>,&rdquo; in last month&rsquo;s </strong></em><strong>SUN</strong><em><strong>.</strong></em></p>

<p class="text-right"><em><strong>&mdash; Ed.</strong></em></p>

<p>I know the cry you write about. I have it sometimes when I drive through the Silk Hope farmland and see the hawk, gust gliding above the upturned field. I cry, not in despair, but to confer a blessing of prosperity upon the farmer&rsquo;s family in their Lowes-panelled kitchen/family room, in the brick veneer ranch-style house (hip roof and nine over six panes rotting and forgotten out back) perched upon the sienna winter meadows. Who is it who says the only cry we have that lacks self-pity is in our dreams?</p>

<p>And now I am reminded of the shame I feel about my family because we did not try to help each other through. We bought Winnebagos and TV dinners and exercise machines and tried the ways in vogue to make ourselves fit, while with the least possible effort and time, passing from one day to the next &mdash; and we had no time for each other. We were self-centered, handsome humans moving from one room to another, down-slippered feet across wall-to-wall carpet, weaving patterns which would never make a web no matter how many times the threads crossed.</p>

<p>I have grown tired and have given up in sorrow because we have not been able to bring our lives together &mdash; because my father has not seen that we are apart; he wanders still around the rooms in foot-worn paths that show no chance of changing, except to become wider from his inability to see ahead, and deeper from the danger of looking back.</p>

<p>MY DREAM: I see two women leaning on fishing poles which are erect in the sand. Sixty years old, gloved hands shoulder high at the pole, their bodies sighing earthward as they hang on staring up the beach. One wears a straw hat tied onto her head by a pink kerchief, probably the same one which secures her rain bonnet when she drives to the grocery at home in the winter. The other wears a visor, its plastic green reflection masking grey eyes, tight lines around her mouth, teeth set as if to hiss the long &ldquo;e&rdquo; sound which seems to make bearing up against the elements less taxing. These two are more than pole sitters for thirsty husbands. Good friends? Probably, judging from the space they share, relaxed and passive, each looking toward the pier. (And oh the summers they have fished this sea.) In my dream I imagine them catching some spot, a croaker or two, sharing the hour in the late afternoon cleaning and scraping fish scales into their drinks. I hear children screaming jubilantly down the beach. I look and when I turn back around, my ladies have abandoned their poles and are walking into the ocean.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Name Withheld<br></p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3345">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p><em>This letter is in response to John Rosenthal&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/2263">Insisting On Love</a>&rdquo; (Issue 63).</em></p>

<p>I, too, feel that the sense of enchantment needs to be restored. By enchantment, I am referring to the delight we find in celebrating the good in each of us. Shall we let the wonder in a child&rsquo;s eyes and the &ldquo;above and beyond the call of duty&rdquo; smile of a bus driver pass through our consciousness like elevator muzak? Shall we not continue the dialogue and not allow the small miracles of human interaction to play on? The romantic call of the search for the one beloved numbs our senses and we become neglectful of the benefits of opening our hearts in everyday life.</p>

<p>An important part of this transformation is the entwining of our lives with the lives of everyone. We need to feel the tear of another as our tear and we need to let the earth laugh, let the city laugh and let the mountains laugh. We can see the reflection of that laughter in the people we encounter. Our honest and loving transactions are further refining mankind&rsquo;s capacity for the attributes of God, a universal act of worship.</p>

<p>Once we have established our friendship with God, mankind and our planet we experience the yoga of everyday life. Token&rsquo;s of God&rsquo;s essence are everywhere and they can serve to help the earth to awaken to its potential. One form of this cultivation of attributes is the path of the householder. John Lennon and Yoko Ono have shown us that a relationship is a tool with which to serve the world. The path of the householder and the yoga of everyday life starts with enchantment and wonder.</p>

<p>Enchantment and wonder are spiritual entities accessible to everyone. The spiritual world underlies our temporal existence and is not merely locked in esoteric mysteries. We are all on a journey through the spiritual world, dreamed about and striven for by our ancestors. Enchantment starts in the open heart, opened to the love, heritage and hope of humanity.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">William Jay Bender<br>Roanoke, Virginia</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3275">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>My deepest gratitude to John Rosenthal for his essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/2263">Insisting On Love</a>&rdquo; in<em> </em>Volume I of <strong>The Sun</strong><em> </em>anthology, <em>A Bell Ringing in the Empty Sky</em>. My God, you people have me saying things like &ldquo;deepest gratitude&rdquo; and meaning it. I don&rsquo;t normally say things like &ldquo;deepest gratitude&rdquo; because I don&rsquo;t usually feel it. So much of what goes on in life today boils down to wolves in sheep&rsquo;s clothing &mdash; and just as bad, sheep in wolves&rsquo; clothing. Not much running around stark naked. A little stark-naked love is what we need, not fear feigning as love. A little root truth is what we need, a little liberation, freckled and towheaded.</p>

<p>Rosenthal mentions Henry Miller, the iconoclast&rsquo;s iconoclast, a massively liberating force. Miller&rsquo;s books were banned in this country until 1963 or so, but it wasn&rsquo;t pornography that made that happen; pornography was running rampant in this country in 1963. I have no use for pornography. The Gulf War was pornography, the network packaging of that war was pornography, General Schwarzkopf dancing with Mickey Mouse for the whole world to see &mdash; <em>that</em> is pornography, and I don&rsquo;t need a Supreme Court decision to tell me this. I am fifty-three years old, I&rsquo;m a battered child, I&rsquo;ve been to hell and back, and my innocence is intact. When I say &ldquo;spiritual&rdquo; I mean <em>spiritual</em>. Spirituality is a ferocious joy that consumes hate and fear, and it was Miller&rsquo;s <em>joy</em> that was being suppressed, joy that causes the fear juice to squirt into the veins of those terrified of their own core innocence. People who bring this fundamental truth into focus are labeled dangerous, and they are dangerous to those living on the dark side of the moon, those with a twisted desire to block out the sun. Rosenthal is one of those dangerous men.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ll go nose to nose with anyone who thinks this is new age pie-in-the-sky drivel. <strong>The Sun</strong> is not &ldquo;new age.&rdquo; New age is jargon and jargon is a trap. Jargon tends to confine, thwart, make simplistic. <strong>The Sun</strong> ignites something in me, sheds light on some invisible, intangible source, a place children recognize effortlessly, a place where the catch phrase &ldquo;life on life&rsquo;s terms&rdquo; should apply. The formidable forces that hold us prisoner today do not represent life on life&rsquo;s terms, they represent life on death&rsquo;s terms; they should be resisted and rejected. <strong>The Sun</strong> tends toward this core place, and that&rsquo;s what sets it apart. <strong>The Sun</strong> has its eye on the lodestar.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">John Bennett<br>Ellensburg, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
